this amplitude is retained, as illustrated by the numerical example in Fig.~\ref{fig:mattercreation_h.eps}.
Thus, the power spectrum of the primordial gravitational waves
evaluated at the end of the genesis phase is given by
\begin{eqnarray}
{\cal P}_h^{(p)}(k)=\frac{2k^2}{\pi^2{\cal G} c_ta_G^2}.
\end{eqnarray}
In contrast to the gravitational waves from inflation,
the primordial spectrum is blue, and hence
gravitational waves could be relevant observationally only at high frequencies.


